article.headline: UCLA 86, Washington 84 (OT)
article.story: SEATTLE (AP) -- Even when things got crazy at the end of regulation, T.J. Cummings and Trevor Ariza never considered losing. Cummings had 22 points and 11 rebounds and Dijon Thompson scored 13, including two free throws with 10.5 seconds remaining in overtime that lifted UCLA to an 86-84 win over Washington on Saturday night. "We showed a lot of poise," Cummings said. "I was really proud of us. That's something we've shown a lot in the last two games, and we've been on the road. That's big for us." Ariza, a freshman, scored five of his 21 points in overtime as the Bruins (8-3, 4-0 Pac-10) survived 24 turnovers. "We never had it on our minds we were going to take a loss," Cummings said. "We had it on our minds we would win. Even though we turned the ball over down the stretch, we still showed a lot of poise and confidence." The Bruins seemed poised to coast to an easy victory until Washington (5-7, 0-4) charged back in the final 3{ minutes, getting the crowd involved by spreading the floor and letting the guards break for the basket. "It coincided with our defensive pressure," Huskies coach Lorenzo Romar said. "I thought our pressure really picked up and it gave us some energy. It really got us going." After Thompson's free throws, the Huskies had a chance to force another overtime when Will Conroy drove and missed a layup as he bumped UCLA's Ryan Hollins in the lane. There was a tangle for the rebound, and officials called a held ball. That gave possession to Washington with 0.2 seconds on the clock. After a timeout, Conroy inbounded for a possible tip-in to Brandon Roy but the horn expired when it touched his fingers. "Coach wanted me to post up whoever was guarding me," Roy said. "I started out close to the baseline and then spun away to get closer to the rim." "Maybe he got bumped," Romar said. "With the amount of time left, that was all we could get off. We got a good look, and we thought we had it." Conroy led Washington with a season-high 29 points. He shot 9-of-15 and had seven rebounds and five assists. "Best game of his career. He did it all," Romar said. Nate Robinson had 18 points, scoring seven in the final three minutes. Roy had 16 for the scrappy Huskies, who have lost seven of nine. "Every game is a learning experience," Romar said. "Every time we've lost, we've lost in a different way. As the season progresses, it's got to help us at the end. I feel we're close to a breakthrough soon." The Bruins have dominated the series, taking their fifth straight victory over Washington and 29 of the last 35 between the schools. But they had to earn this one, and it easily could have swung the other way. "This will help our confidence," Ariza said. "Winning on the road always helps, and so does beating a good team on their court. I didn't want to lose. I didn't think we were going to lose." UCLA led 70-57 with 3:32 to play after Thompson scored twice and Ariza had a three-point play. But Conroy and Robinson each scored 10 points during a 12-2 burst that pulled the Huskies to 72-71. Tre Simmons got free under the hoop for an easy basket, and the Huskies led 75-74 with 44.7 seconds to go. Ariza made one of two free throws to tie it again, and Roy was called for an offensive foul when he drove. Janou Rubin was way off the mark on a runner that would have won it for UCLA at the end of regulation. The Bruins shot 56.7 percent from the floor in the first half, and it seemed like enough to hold up the lead over the final 20 minutes. "We played very well until the second half, when they started to beat us off the dribble," UCLA coach Ben Howland said. "I have to commend them. They really made a valiant comeback. I'm just glad we were able to hang on."
